    "image_with_text_t6KzFw": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CcwiLn": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/asiafiasco/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Charlene Akuamoah</span></a> approaches costume design as a form of world-building, where character always comes first. She often starts by letting real-life moments guide her, resulting in work that feels intuitive and precise at the same time. Rooted in story, each costume tells as much about a character as their words or actions do.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CcwiLn"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/GetplentyLook7.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "text_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "scheme-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 36,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_wKVLmh": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CLbqn8": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q: </strong>3 words your friends/family would use to describe you?</p><p><strong>A: </strong>Funny, fashionable and ambitious.</p><p><strong>Q: </strong>Your work spans design, styling, and illustration. How do these different creative languages inform each other in your process?</p><p><strong>A</strong>: Each one is a vehicle to communicate a story, feeling, or time period. They work so well together to move different narratives forward and I’ve been lucky enough to be able to combine all three to communicate exactly what it is that a character needs. They all lean on each other in different ways when I’m stuck trying to figure someone out.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CLbqn8"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/GetplentyLook2.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "image_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "scheme-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 0,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_NjQ3EM": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_ENV8fL": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q:</strong> If you could dress one character for the screen, who would it be and what would they wear?</p><p><strong>A:</strong> I LOVE this question. My answer will be different depending on what day you get me. But currently, I’d really like to dress an Alternative Black character in a highly stylized film. I’d dress them in Ann Demeulemeester, Rei Kawakubo, Vintage Gareth Pugh, Vintage McQueen and some Vivienne Westwood. </p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_ENV8fL"
      ],
